FT  24 MAY 94 / International Company News: BCI to strengthen links with
other banks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Banca Commerciale Italiana, the recently privatised Italian bank, is
planning to strengthen cross-shareholdings with Commerzbank of Germany and
Creditanstalt of Austria.
The BCI board yesterday authorised negotiations for the purchase of a 1 per
cent stake in Commerzbank, which already owns just under 3 per cent of the
Italian bank and is represented on the board.
BCI said talks were already under way with the German bank.
BCI also said last night that it was interested in buying 3 per cent of the
voting shares of Creditanstalt, a holding equivalent to 2 per cent of the
overall capital of the Vienna-based institution, which is being privatised.
Creditanstalt, which also has a representative on the BCI board, has been a
BCI shareholder since the Italian bank was founded last century.
BCI's name had already been mentioned in rumours about the formation of a
consortium to buy into the capital of the Austrian bank to prevent control
falling into unfriendly hands. BCI said last night that it had simply
declared its willingness to buy shares, and it would be up to the Austrians
to decide how such an operation should be carried out.
