<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAY 94 / International Company News: Desjardins Laurentian in profit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Desjardins Laurentian Financial, the financial services group controlled by
the Desjardins credit union movement, reported first-quarter profits of
CDollars 9.2m (USDollars 6.66m) or 18 cents a share, after a CDollars 9.5m
reorganisation charge, on revenues of CDollars 983m.
It was the first reporting period since the December 1993 takeover of the
Laurentian Group by Desjardins to form a financial services and banking
group with corporate assets of CDollars 55bn.
Desjardins Laurentian, with CDollars 22bn assets, brings together life
insurance, general insurance, trust operations, investment banking and
consumer banking with subsidiaries in Canada, the US and Britain. It is 7.7
per cent held by La Victoire of France and its shares are publicly traded in
Toronto and Montreal.
Imperial Life, one of its biggest units, earned CDollars 59,000 in the first
quarter after a CDollars 2.5m special charge by its British subsidiary. This
compares with CDollars 5.6m a year earlier. Performance was also affected by
the north American property market collapse, but overall Canadian and US
operations were still profitable.
Desjardins Laurentian will set aside CDollars 40m this year to cover
reorganisation costs. 'The full benefits will be felt in 1996,' said Mr
Humberto Santos, president.
Two life units may be merged but asset sales are unlikely, he added.
</TEXT>
