<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAY 94 / UK Company News: Steiner resigns from Amstrad
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Bernard Steiner, Amstrad's sales and marketing director, yesterday
resigned from the consumer electronic group run by Mr Alan Sugar 'to persue
other interests.'
The company gave no other explanation for Mr Steiner's sudden departure
which was said to be 'amicable.'
Mr Sugar, Amstrad's founder and chairman, originally recruited Mr Steiner
from Sansui Electronics in 1991 to take charge of Amstrad's sales and
marketing in mainland Europe and Australia.
Mr Steiner, an Italian in his late-40s, was formerly managing director of
Sansui Europe. During a long career in the electronics business, he has
worked for Olivetti of Italy, where he was concerned with the Acorn and
Triumph Adler business, and for Sony's German subsidiary.
He is the latest in a series of resignations from Amstrad in recent years,
and these include Mr Peter Thoms, the former finance director, who resigned
in July 1992, and Mr Robert Watkins, technical director, who resigned in
January 1993.
Mr Watkins, who left to join Binatone, the rival electronics group,
subsequently returned to take charge of Dancall Radio which Amstrad acquired
last September.
Amstrad, has been looking for a chief executive for the past 18 months, and
is expected to announce an appointment shortly.
</TEXT>
