<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAY 94 / UK Company News: Betterware makes Pounds 14mbut warns on
outlook
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Betterware, the direct home shopping group, yesterday reported a 3 per cent
increase in full year pre-tax profits held back by lower interest receipts
and the absence of a large exceptional gain which bolstered the previous
year's figures.
Profits for the year to February 26 increased from Pounds 13.7m to Pounds
14.1m on turnover which grew by 12 per cent to Pounds 63.2m (Pounds 56.3m).
The growth in turnover was underpinned by a 14 per cent increase in UK sales
which rose to Pounds 50.5m and a fourfold increase of sales in France to
Pounds 2.8m.
The pre-tax result included net interest receipts of Pounds 823,000 (Pounds
1.14m) while the comparable profit figure was inflated by an exceptional
Pounds 1.53m VAT credit.
Earnings increased to 9.4p (8.4p) helped by a lower tax charge of Pounds
4.39m (Pounds 5.14m). A proposed final dividend of 1.95p makes a 2.6p (2p)
total. The shares closed 5p lower at 123p.
Mr Walter Goldsmith, chairman, said it had been 'a challenging year' but
that Betterware had emerged stronger as a result of a series of steps
including the opening of a new Pounds 10m distribution centre near
Birmingham, the strengthening of senior management and further expansion in
continental Europe.
Operating profits increased by 5.5 per cent to Pounds 13.2m (Pounds 12.5m).
However, excluding the VAT refund underlying operating profits grew by 19
per cent.
UK margins were higher, helped by a greater emphasis on product development.
The UK average order level held steady at about Pounds 8. That compared with
Pounds 13 in the French operations, which were started two years ago and
made about Pounds 300,000 in profits last year, and Pounds 10 in Spain where
Betterware began door-to-door sales in September.
Mr Andrew Cohen, chief executive, said the group plans to begin operations
in Germany in the current financial year and will invest about Pounds 1m in
the start-up.
Commenting on the outlook Mr Goldsmith cautioned that sales in the first
quarter had been held back by start-up problems at the new distribution
centre, although he said these had now been resolved. He added that sales
were also affected by 'the consumer uncertainty' of recent weeks but said
sales were now showing 'a distinctly more positive picture'.
COMMENT
The years of strong growth in the maturing UK market are probably over but
the group plans to maintain UK margins by encouraging customers to increase
their average spend and by cutting its purchase costs. However, the real
engine for future growth should be the new operations in continental Europe.
Against this, teething problems at Birmingham and other factors have hit
sales and orders at the start of the current year. Overall, pre-tax profits
are likely to edge higher to about Pounds 14.5m this year producing earnings
of 9.5p. The shares have fallen sharply over the past year and are now
trading on a reasonable prospective p/e of 12.9.
</TEXT>
