<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAY 94 / Observer: Bad survey
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir James Blyth, chief executive of Boots, doesn't seem too keen on
chartered surveyors.
Why was it, he asked a property conference yesterday, that the surveyors
employed by Boots had to be trained from first principles in almost every
area of commercial life from the rudiments of marketing to constructing a
business plan? And why was it, he continued, that while so many Boots
managers work in jobs remote from their professional training, all the
surveyors in the company are in positions directly associated with property?
Surely, he argued, surveyors should be capable of pursuing broader business
careers.
Could this view have anything to do with the fact that Boots' outgoing
chairman, Sir Christopher Benson, is a well-known chartered surveyor?
</TEXT>
