<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAY 94 / Shake-up of electricity pool backed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The biggest companies in England and Wales are hoping for a cut in
electricity prices after senior power-industry executives agreed to back a
campaign to allow electricity to be bought and sold outside the wholesale
trading pool.
Companies such as Imperial Chemical Industries have long complained that by
being forced to trade through the pool, rather than conclude simpler
bilateral agreements with electricity generators, they have paid higher
prices for power than are justified.
The power industry, including the generators, has been sceptical of moves to
allow pool bypass arrangements, arguing that it might lead to companies
trading outside the pool to avoid paying a share of costs needed to run the
electricity system.
However, pressure for a change of stance has grown in recent months after
Offer, the industry's regulator, asked the industry to give the matter
urgent consideration.
It is partly in response to this that the majority of a pool strategy group,
made up of senior executives representing all parts of the industry, is
recommending that arrangements be developed for non-pool trading.
Representatives of the large generating companies, which previously were
among the most sceptical about change, now support themove.
However, about a third of the strategy group, mainly representatives of
regional electricity companies, oppose it. They argue that hedging
instruments, known as contracts for differences, already in effect allow for
non-pool trading.
Opponents fear that setting up bypass arrangements might be expensive but
would produce little benefit for either the industry or its customers. It
might also make the system less transparent.
Mr Ken Green, utilities buyer at ICI, yesterday welcomed the view of the
group majority. Yet he warned that any bypass arrangements would have to
include incentives to encourage generators to make non-pool deals.
'If they do, then there is a real chance that prices can drop for large
users,' he said.
The pool strategy group in its report commissioned by the pool executive on
reform has also rejected wholesale changes to the way in which prices are
determined.
Offer last year asked the pool to consider a system through which generators
would be paid the price they offered for each generating unit, rather than
the 'marginal price', which is determined by the most expensive generated
unit needed to run the system.
Some large users considered this to be a fairer, more logical system. But
several have changed their minds after considering the issue; one fear is
that it would lead to even more complication in a highly complex trading
system.
It is understood Offer has received a hostile response to the bidding
changes and is unlikely to push for reform.
In another recommendation, the pool strategy group has said permanent
arrangements should be set up to transfer responsibility for some of the
'uplift', or administration costs, of running the pool to the National Grid
company.
The committee suggests a more refined system than the temporary one put in
place earlier this year.
Under this, various cost elements would be separated and National Grid would
only be given control of those parts where its management could make a
difference. The rest would stay with the pool.
The pool intends to reach conclusions by September.
</TEXT>
<XX>
