<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAY 94 / Motor trade and BT to create data 'highway'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British Telecommunications and two retail motor-trade associations have
joined forces to create what they hope will become an electronic data
interchange 'highway' for the motor industry.
The project, which links BT with the Retail Motor Industry Federation and
the Automotive Distribution Federation, is designed to allow low-cost
communications and the undertaking of a wide range of transactions between
all parties involved in selling, financing and maintaining vehicles.
To start with transmissions will relate to vehicle servicing and invoicing
between dealers and customers. However, 'it will develop to encompass
product and parts ordering, service information and advice, finance,
insurance and much more', said Mr Trevor Parkerson, business development
manager of the RMI, which represents most sections of the retail motor trade
including about 7,000 franchised car dealers.
None of the main carmakers and importers however, has been directly involved
in creating the network. The Society of Motor Manufacturers and Traders, the
main trade voice of the manufacturers and component producers, has been
developing a separate data highway - although this is concerned more with
manufacturer-supplier relationships than with retailing. But both the RMI
and SMMT agreed yesterday that the systems could be 'very compatible'.
As for manufacturers of cars and commercial vehicles, each has developed its
own data interchange systems with dealers. Mr Alan Pulham, head of the RMI's
National Franchised Dealers Association, agreed its members would need
persuading to adopt the planned highway's protocols for their own
transactions.
Called the Automotive Transactions Highway, the RMI-initiated venture can
use existing dealer-management systems hardware.
The first 'Fleetlink' enables motor retailers to exchange purchase and
service orders with fleet customers with a start-up cost of Pounds 300 and
running costs of about Pounds 50 a month.
</TEXT>
