<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAY 94 / British Council theft linked to gang behind Pounds 1/2m
fraud
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A gang responsible for defrauding the British Council of more than Pounds
500,000 appears to be behind a cheque theft that has cost the
government-funded body more than Pounds 70,000, the Treasury has admitted.
In its response to a critical report from the Commons public accounts
committee on the original fraud, the Treasury said subsequent police
inquiries uncovered the theft of two blank cheques from the council, the
body which promotes UK cultural interests overseas.
One was used to draw Pounds 70,104.60 in April 1992. The other, which has
not been presented, has been cancelled.
Police have concluded that the theft was carried out by the same gang that
stole Pounds 520,072 by transferring funds electronically into the overseas
bank accounts of bogus suppliers in December 1992.
A British Council employee has been arrested on suspicion of involvement in
the theft, and has been suspended pending the outcome of police and council
inquiries.
Police believe that the discovery of the cheque theft has established an
internal connection between the gang that committed the earlier fraud and
the council, the Treasury said.
Mr John Hanson, the council's director-general, told the public accounts
committee in December that the gang had access to 'insider information'.
In its report on the fraud published in March, the committee criticised the
failure to identify the source of the information.
</TEXT>
