<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAY 94 / Ashdown puts poll at heart of platform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Paddy Ashdown yesterday put the pledge of a referendum on further moves
towards European integration at the centre of the Liberal Democrats'
European election platform.
Launching a manifesto designed to appeal to disaffected Tory voters, the
Liberal Democrat leader underlined his party's support for the goal of a
single European currency and increased integration on defence.
But he said Britain should retain a veto over executive decisions on
monetary and strategic defence policy by the Council of Ministers. This
would be in the context of an extension of qualified majority voting to
areas such as troop deployments and Common Agricultural Policy reform.
At an upbeat press conference Mr Ashdown was at pains to adopt a balanced
stance, saying a single currency would have disadvantages as well as
advantages and insisting that Britain would retain its right not to have
soldiers committed to specific conflicts.
Commenting on the manifesto's pledge to seek 'popular assent' if the 1996
intergovernmental conference proposed 'fundamental changes', he said there
were 'nine chances in 10' that a referendum would be the appropriate
mechanism.
Yesterday's 28-page document called for an independent central bank but
mentions a single currency only once, saying the party would 'move in step
with Britain's European partners' towards this goal.
It takes a similarly measured tone on employee rights. It says: 'We want to
see an effective framework of individual employment rights throughout
Europe, while rejecting the centralised straitjacket of a European-wide
minimum wage or maximum 35-hour week.'
On the reform of EU institutions, it calls for cuts in the size of the
European Commission, the Council of Ministers and the European parliament.
But it says the parliament should be given equal legislative rights to the
council.
The manifesto insists that Britain's right not to have defence forces
committed to combat must be maintained, but makes clear that, even if it
exercised this right, Britain would have to help pay for its EU partners to
deploy their troops. What the document has to say on defence will be
scrutinised particularly carefully by the Tories in light of the strong
Liberal Democrat challenge anticipated in south-west England, which is
highly dependent on defence.
On the environment, the party would seek to enforce the principle that
polluters should pay for the damage they cause, as well as extending the
powers of the European Environment Agency. It would phase out existing
nuclear power stations by the year 2020 and 'rapidly develop' alternative
power sources, such as wind, wave and tidal power.
</TEXT>
