<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAY 94 / Apology sought from MP over bill
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Lady Olga Maitland, the Conservative MP for Sutton and Cheam, came under
further pressure yesterday to apologise for her role in wrecking the
backbench bill which sought to establish new rights for the disabled.
Miss Betty Boothroyd, the Speaker, told the Commons she had made
representations to Lady Olga.
The MP has recently returned to Westminster after a visit with a
parliamentary delegation to Malawi.
Ms Liz Lynne, who speaks for the Liberal Democrats on health, asked whether
Lady Olga was prepared to apologise for 'misleading the House about the
drafting of amendments tabled in her name' to the disability (civil rights)
bill.
Lady Olga, who was not in her place in the Commons chamber when the issue
was raised yesterday, had insisted in earlier exchanges that she was
responsible for the amendments. She said: 'I sought consultation, but it
would be totally unfair to suggest that they came from any other source.'
Opposition MPs claim that her amendments were among those drafted by
parliamentary counsel referred to by Mr Nicholas Scott, minister responsible
for the disabled, when he apologised for misleading the House during the
controversy over the bill.
Referring to a demonstration staged earlier in the day, Miss Boothroyd said
some disabled people were 'unfortunately encouraged by some members of the
House to crawl up the steps at St Stephen's entrance for the benefit of the
media'.
She reaffirmed that the disabled were able to gain access to the House
through New Palace Yard.
</TEXT>
