<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAY 94 / 'Undemocratic' moves to cut red tape spark anger
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government's de-regulation bill was given a third reading amid backbench
protests that sweeping new powers for ministers to cut red tape were
undemocratic.
The measure, which was passed by 291 votes to 242, will give ministers the
ability to repeal or amend de-regulation laws through orders, which can be
dealt with on a single Commons vote rather than through the more lengthy
legislative process.
Mr Tim Sainsbury, industry minister, said: 'The order-making power is needed
for the timely removal of laws imposing burdens on business. We need an
effective mechanism to deal with these burdens both now and in the future.'
He rejected Labour-led calls for a five-year limit on ministers' new powers
and for an annual de-regulation bill, saying a time limit would not be
appropriate.
Some Tory backbenchers opposed the new powers. Mr Richard Shepherd, MP for
Aldridge Brownhills, intervened to ask Mr Sainsbury: 'Why is it necessary to
have these extraordinary powers that contradict our constitution?' He
accused the government of trying to bring an administrative device to govern
England, Scotland and Wales as it governs Ulster.
Mr Gary Waller, MP for Keighley, said: 'A general power to create or amend
the law, even with limitations, is a power which should certainly give us as
parliamentarians pause for thought, and we should at the very least set a
time limit on its application.
'I am afraid that at the end of the day to place untrammelled power in the
hands of ministers, not of this government but of any government, is
something which I have to reject.'
Mr Derek Fatchett, Labour's industry spokesman, said no Labour government
would use the powers, which he described as 'an abuse of the House of
Commons'.
Earlier, Labour had attacked plans to reduce regulations governing standards
for operators of heavy trucks, fearing the move would harm road safety.
Mr Fatchett said: 'All the evidence points to the need for the current
system to be maintained or toughened up - not weakened.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
