<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAY 94 / Outsider to run accounts firm
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Robson Rhodes, the UK's 15th-largest accountancy firm, yesterday appointed a
businessman as its chief operating officer.
Mr Peter Turnbull, former managing director of Lex Service, the largest UK
car distribution and leasing group, will be operational head of the firm.
The move is a highly unusual example of the appointment of an outsider to
help manage the running of a professional practice. Although Mr Turnbull
qualified as an accountant, most senior positions in accountancy firms are
filled from within by accountants who have spent their careers in public
practice.
A number of firms have hired specialist outsiders in areas such as marketing
and human resources, but few have made appointments at such a senior level.
Robson Rhodes itself hired Mr Ray Pierce, former head of the Mortgage
Corporation, as chief executive two years ago. He left last September when
he was headhunted to become managing director of Guardian Direct, an
insurance subsidiary of Guardian Royal Exchange.
Mr Turnbull qualified as a chartered accountant in 1967 and spent 20 years
working for Lex Service as group finance director and chief executive of
Volvo Concessionaires before becoming chief executive of APA Group, an
automotive consultancy.
Robson Rhodes said that Mr Turnbull would be responsible for implementing
the firm's strategy to meet its goals.
</TEXT>
