<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAY 94 / Miners reject weekend shifts deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
More than 2,500 British Coal pit employees have missed out on a Pounds 6,000
one-off bonus after accepting the advice of their unions to refuse an
agreement which would commit them to working at weekends for the first time.
Failure to accept the deal also means they will receive less in severance
pay should future employers make them redundant.
They will receive the statutory minimum of Pounds 6,150 rather than the
Pounds 27,000 maximum available under the agreement signed by 9,200 of their
colleagues.
Most of those who refused to sign the working hours and redundancy pay
package are in the Yorkshire region, the heartland of Mr Arthur Scargill's
National Union of Mineworkers. Some 44 per cent of miners there accepted the
deal, whereas 90 per cent of miners in the Midlands, where the Union of
Democratic Mineworkers is predominant, took the package.
The imbalance is likely to hit the attractions of British Coal's central
north region. Potential bidders have been put off because of the perceived
militancy of the NUM.
British Coal said yesterday that it had warned miners they would not be
eligible for the increased pay-off unless they had signed up by last Friday.
However, there is likely to be pressure from prospective bidders for British
Coal to extend the deadline. They are unlikely to want to inherit a group of
workers who are working on varied contracts.
The UDM said that some of its members had tried to sign up on Monday but
were turned away. Mr Mick Stephens, a union official, said some miners had
been given less notice than others about the terms of the offer.
</TEXT>
