FT  24 MAY 94 / Dublin pledges security review
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Republic of Ireland is to review security after a failed bomb attack in
Dublin at the weekend, which the loyalist paramilitary group, the Ulster
Volunteer Force, claimed responsibility for.
At the formal reopening of the Shannon-Erne waterway on the Northern Irish
border yesterday, Mr Dick Spring, Irish foreign minister, announced a
security review and said that efforts would be made to restart political
talks in the north.
Ms Maire Geoghegan-Quinn, the Irish justice minister, said there was concern
about possible further attacks after the Dublin bomb.
Mr James Molyneaux, leader of the Ulster Unionist party, yesterday blamed
the 'ambiguity and uncertainty' of the British government over Northern
Ireland for encouraging loyalist paramilitaries 'to achieve a balance of
terror'. Yet he said he was encouraged by reports that the combined
leadership of the loyalist paramilitaries was planning to meet this week to
consider his recent call for a ceasefire.
The Rev Roy Magee, a Presbyterian minister, met leaders of the UVF and UFF
in Belfast yesterday. He said he believed the Dublin attack was a 'warning
shot', not the start of an continuing campaign south of the border.
He said the lack of an IRA response to the joint declaration meant the
loyalist paramilitaries considered themselves in a 'state of war' and were
making the point that they must be dealt with.
