<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAY 94 / Subsidies for farming attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON MAITLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Arable farmers in England are receiving Pounds 759m a year in subsidies from
taxpayers which bring virtually no environmental benefits, the Council for
the Protection of Rural England said yesterday.
Publishing a regional and county breakdown of Common Agricultural Policy
subsidies to arable farmers, Mr Paul Wynne, the council's land use officer,
said: 'The public is getting a bad deal. This expenditure compensates
farmers for reduced price support but bears no relationship to environmental
quality or management and asks remarkably little of them in return.'
By contrast, he said, schemes which actively encouraged English farmers to
adopt environmentally friendly practices received just Pounds 27.1m in the
past financial year.
The survey highlights how the largest subsidy payments go to farmers in the
country's most intensive cereal-growing regions, where wild plant and animal
life are especially vulnerable.
The government's Countryside Survey last year showed that the number of
plant species had fallen 30 per cent in arable fields between 1978 and 1990.
Lincolnshire arable farmers received the biggest payments last year,
totalling nearly Pounds 68m, of which Pounds 55m was for growing crops and
Pounds 12m was for leaving part of their land idle as 'set-aside'.
Humberside ranked second in the survey, with its arable farmers receiving
Pounds 40m, of which Pounds 7.4m was for set-aside, and Norfolk came third.
English farmers were paid Pounds 253 a hectare for the 15 per cent of their
land they were required to set aside in order to cut grain surpluses. They
received Pounds 140 a hectare for growing cereals, and Pounds 400 a hectare
for oilseeds such as rape.
The council pointed out that only the set-aside payments, which make up
Pounds 125m of the total, have environmental conditions attached to them.
Mr Wynne urged the government to make all arable compensation payments
conditional on farmers adopting 'positive management' of the environment.
</TEXT>
