<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAY 94 / Treasury guided over the rapids: Peter Marsh on why Sir
Terry Burns called in a management consultant
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In the Treasury she is known as Sir Terry Burns's right-hand woman. Ms Wendy
Pritchard, a management consultant, was called in by Sir Terry, Treasury
permanent secretary, about a year ago.
Her brief is to facilitate management changes and encourage officials to
open up more to the outside world.
The Treasury, the most powerful government department, is undergoing a
period of restructuring to reduce the number of officials in its top layer
and to involve more junior staff in decision-making.
Sir Terry, permanent secretary since 1991, has also called in Sir Colin
Southgate, chairman of Thorn EMI and one of Britain's most highly regarded
industrialists, to supervise a detailed review of the way top managers
operate.
While Sir Colin has a specific remit which will last until the autumn and is
tied to a formal scrutiny of Treasury operations announced in the last
Budget, Ms Pritchard has a more fluid role.
During the past year she has come to the Treasury every few weeks to talk to
top officials and advise on how they link with outsiders and their own
departments. She has also participated in three special meetings of the
Treasury's management board - a group of eight senior civil servants - to
review how the department operates.
In an interview, Ms Pritchard was keen to elaborate on her general approach
to consultancy but refused to talk about her specific role at the Treasury
because she said this would breach confidences.
She described her work in big organisations as 'rather like having to drill
down through layers of sediment to find out about the way things were done
years ago and which often influence how things are done now. The process of
change is often about unpicking these past practices and suggesting
something new'.
When working with big organisations, she says she tries to stand back and
appreciate the pressures on top managers and the way they make decisions.
She said part of her job with clients was to identify the 'antibodies to
change'.
'Managers have to try to find time to react not just to the events of today
but longer-term strategies,' said Ms Pritchard. 'That can be difficult when
external changes (in political events and business practice) are taking
place at such a huge rate. In the past, managers used to have to cope with
the occasional burst of rapids while now it is white water all the way.'
Ms Pritchard has been a freelance management consultant for five years. She
has won general respect for her approach in the Treasury, where morale has
suffered because of criticism for underestimating the extent of the early
1990s recession and for mistakes linked to Britain's departure from the
European exchange rate mechanism.
One person close to the Treasury said: 'She is operating in the way you
would expect of a counsellor, talking to officials about their relationship
with each other and with their more junior staff. She is very interested in
the process of management rather than being driven by the need to implement
solutions.'
Another person knowledgeable about her role said: 'Occasionally I have the
feeling she has been over-deferential to top officials and has been too keen
to listen to them rather than impose new ideas. She's very anxious to see
the Treasury take on a more participative approach to management which
carries everyone along with it, rather than the normal Treasury style which
is to form a small group to tackle a specific policy area and crack on with
the job by involving as few people as possible.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
