<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAY 94 / Visit lifts hopes on Malaysia trade ban
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KIERAN COOKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
There is speculation that a Malaysian ban on giving government contracts to
British companies might be lifted soon following a surprise visit to
Malaysia by Mr Richard Needham, the trade minister, Kieran Cooke writes.
Mr Needham arrived yesterday and was scheduled to have a meeting with Dr
Mahathir Mohamad, the Malaysian prime minister.
Mr Needham said he was carrying a letter from Mr John Major to Dr Mahathir
and expressed the hope that the ban would be lifted soon. He added: 'We have
so many things to do in common, not only in business but in education,
health care and so on.'
Malaysia imposed its ban at the end of February after critical comments
about the government in the British press. In particular Kuala Lumpur
reacted angrily to a report in The Sunday Times which alleged that a British
company was prepared to offer bribes to Dr Mahathir in exchange for a
contract.
The ban is believed to have cost British companies many millions of pounds
of business. Mr Needham has been among the more vocal critics of what he has
considered to be irresponsible reporting about Malaysia in the British
media.
</TEXT>
