<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAY 94 / Move to cut truck red tape attacked
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Government plans to reduce regulations governing standards for operators of
heavy trucks were attacked by Labour in the Commons yesterday.
Fears that the move would harm road safety were voiced during the report
stage debate on the deregulation and contracting-out bill, which the
government says is aimed at cutting red tape and reducing the bureaucratic
burden on business.
The bill provides that operators of heavy lorries would no longer have to
reapply for their licences every five years.
Mr Derek Fatchett, Labour trade and industry spokesman, said: 'All the
evidence points to the need for the current system to be maintained or
toughened up - not weakened. Our concern is that the government will be
giving a wink and a nod to those who may take short cuts with safety.'
Mr Steven Norris, junior transport minister, accused Labour MPs of 'quite
deliberately confusing the issues of safety and regulation'. They had
assumed deregulation automatically compromised safety. He said the bill did
not affect the power of a licensing authority to take vehicles off the road
and bring legal action against operators for sub-standard practices.
</TEXT>
