<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAY 94 / Blair to set out his policy approach
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Tony Blair, front-runner for the succession to the Labour leadership,
will today set out some of the central planks of his political philosophy in
his first significant speech since the death of John Smith, the former
leader.
In an address to a conference organised by the Institute of Economic
Affairs, the free-market think-tank, Mr Blair is expected to spell out the
case of Labour's modernisers for a new relationship between the individual
and the community.
Mr Blair's friends insisted last night that the speech - addressing the
links between crime and family breakdown - had been planned since last
November and did not mark the opening shot in his leadership campaign.
The shadow cabinet decided last week that none of the contenders should
stake their claims until after the European elections on June 9.
But the shadow home secretary is expected to develop some of the main themes
that have distinguished his approach to Labour's policymaking from that of
the traditionalists on the left of the party.
Mr Blair will stress that Labour's call for much greater social cohesion
does not imply a drive to re-impose uniform state controls. Instead,
restoring the country's social fabric would be the route to individual
self-improvement.
He is likely to emphasise also that his party's commitment to extending the
rights of individuals is accompanied by a clear appreciation of individual
responsibility.
</TEXT>
