<DOCNO>FT942-7870</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EEYBKABEFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940524
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAY 94 / US groups face ban by aid banks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
European countries are threatening to bar US companies from bidding for
contracts financed by the multinational development banks in reprisal for
the US's repeated failure to honour its funding pledges to these
institutions.
Mr Rene Legrand, a director representing Belgium, France, Italy, Spain and
Switzerland at the Manila-based Asian Development Bank, warned recently that
the countries he represents might seek measures to prevent countries in
significant arrears of payments, principally the US, from bidding on ADB
projects.
'One might say that bearing the moral burden of one contributor is beginning
to exhaust the patience of some of the others,' Mr Legrand said.
The US has accumulated a total of Dollars 847m (Pounds 562m) of arrears on
money it has promised to the World Bank and the regional development banks,
with the Asian Development Bank accounting for a large portion of the total,
as Congress has often proved reluctant to fund the promises made by the
administration.
But at the same time, the US is usually the most vociferous member in
calling for management reforms and greater transparency at the multilateral
development banks.
Mr Lloyd Bentsen, US treasury secretary, has complained repeatedly of the
embarrassment of being so far in arrears.
'You know, we go into these meetings and we bang our fists on the desk and
insist that we are a major stockholder and we think our policies should be
put into effect. But we don't even keep up with the rent. We have a past-due
notice on the door,' Mr Bentsen said yesterday.
The treasury had proposed an allocation of Dollars 87m in this year's budget
towards paying off past arrears, but the House of Representatives
appropriations committee has trimmed that to around Dollars 20m.
The House also eliminated a promised Dollars 100m contribution to the
Enhanced Structural Adjustment Facility, through which the International
Monetary Fund lends money at subsidised rates to the very poorest countries.
</TEXT>
