<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAY 94 / Sanaa hit by missile explosion
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By AP
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SANAA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A Scud missile exploded yesterday in a densely populated neighbourhood of
the Yemeni capital as northern troops pushed into southern oil fields, AP
reports from Sanaa.
Reporters who got to the Al-Qaa area of Sanaa before soldiers sealed it off
saw five demolished houses. At least one body was seen being pulled from
under debris. The missile landed close to the city's Jumhouriya Hospital.
President Ali Abdullah Saleh, the northern leader, has a residence about 800
meters from the scene.
International relief agencies prepared to move up to 5,000 Somali refugees
from a camp on the front lines in the civil war. Refugees say at least 175
Somalis have been killed in cross fire.
Yemen collapsed into all-out war between northern and southern forces on May
5. The conservative north had united with the formerly Marxist south on May
22 1990, to form the first multi-party democracy on the Arabian peninsula.
In a broadcast on Sanaa radio, a military official said northern troops had
on Sunday seized a key military base in Ataq, the capital of oil-producing
Shabwa province.
The south on Friday announced it was seceding, a declaration rejected by the
north. Ali Salem al-Beidh, who was vice president of unified Yemen, was
named president of the south's newly declared Democratic Republic of Yemen.
In Washington, Mr Mike McCurry, State Department spokesman, said: 'The
United States does not believe the critical issues which will shape the
future of Yemen should be decided in the heat of battle. We will therefore
not respond to the al-Beidh declaration.'
</TEXT>
