<HEADLINE>
FT  24 MAY 94 / Zhu eases credit restrictions on state enterprises
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY WALKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BEIJING
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Zhu Rongji, China's senior vice premier in charge of the economy, has
signalled an easing of tight credit restrictions on lending to ailing state
enterprises and has also appealed for greater efforts to increase grain and
cotton production.
Mr Zhu's remarks, published on the front pages yesterday of main Chinese
newspapers, indicate growing official anxiety over labour unrest in
cash-starved state factories and also worries about a serious shortfall in
cotton production accompanied by signs of growing agitation among peasants.
Addressing two separate economic forums in the past two weeks attended by
provincial leaders from China's central and southern provinces, Mr Zhu
called on economic departments and banks to 'help' failing enterprises.
He was quoted as saying that government bodies including financial
institutions should 'make surveys and help enterprises to resume production
and get out of these predicaments'.
The State Statistical Bureau reported that in the first quarter nearly half
the state enterprises were lossmaking. Some estimates put 'triangular debt'
 -enterprises owing money to each other for raw materials and finished
products - at Yn300bn (Pounds 23bn).
Mr Zhu, who is also governor of the People's Bank of China, the central
bank, has been under considerable pressure from the powerful state
enterprise lobby to ease credit to save state-run factories from bankruptcy
and avoid the spectre of thousands of workers losing their jobs.
His appeal to officials to 'fully arouse' farmers' enthusiasm for cotton
production reflects deepening government concern over sharp rises in the
cotton price. Textile factories throughout China - the industry is one of
the country's biggest employers - are facing difficulties securing supplies
and some have been obliged to stop production.
Mr Zhu, who has made curtailing inflation a main priority, has been
insisting on continued tight credit policies, but banking statistics for
April showing an increase in the funds of state enterprises indicates an
easing of restrictions is already taking place.
Western economists in Beijing say it is likely the government will continue
to be selective in providing credit. They contrast the latest cautious
easing with the panicky steps taken last September and October to provide
additional funding to loss-making enterprises.
A slight lessening of inflationary pressures - the April and March figures
were down on the rate of growth registered in the first two months of the
year - suggests the government may have some scope for a limited relaxation
of credit.
Mr Zhu's call for an improvement in handling what he called 'relations
between reform, development and stability' coincides with official alarm
about growing unrest among peasants whose returns from their tiny plots are
being squeezed by higher production costs. Farmers are also angry about a
widening gap between country and city, inland and coastal regions. Inflation
has also been rising faster in rural areas than in the city, according to
the latest State Statistical Bureau review, adding to peasant unhappiness.
Mr Ren Jianxin, a senior party official, was quoted at the weekend in the
People's Daily, the Communist party newspaper, as saying at a meeting on
rural instability that the 'security management situation remains extremely
grim nationwide this year'.
Mr Ren called on the security apparatus to 'strengthen the force of their
blows and mercilessly attack serious criminal activities and serious
economic crimes'. He was referring to widespread rural lawlessness,
including banditry, clan feuds, and violent protests against local
officials.
People's Daily also reflected official concerns about stability in a
commentary published yesterday which called for sensitive handling of the
present difficult reform phase, especially rationalisation of state
enterprises and threats to employment.
'When an old balance is broken,' the paper said, 'conflict is unavoidable,
such as the conflict between the centre and the localities, between local
governments and enterprises and between enterprises and their employees.'
China's leaders have, since an important meeting of the Communist party
central committee last November approved a new package of reforms, been
putting heavy emphasis on stability. This has coincided with a crackdown on
any sign of political opposition.
</TEXT>
