<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAY 94 / Company News (This Week): British Airways faces City
concerns - Other companies
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
British Airways' tradition of near break-even fourth-quarter results has
left analysts forecasting full-year pre-tax profits of about Pounds 300m,
against Pounds 185m. However, the tone of today's statement may be more
important than the headline profit. The stock has been weak since
lower-than-expected growth in traffic in April, and there are concerns about
BA's associate USAir.
Thorn EMI: The music, rentals and electronics group, reports full-year
results tomorrow, with pre-tax profits forecast at Pounds 330m-Pounds 340m,
compared with Pounds 286.3m - although that figure is expected to be
adjusted. Attention will focus on the state of the UK consumer market.
Marks and Spencer: Tomorrow's annual results presentation should confirm M&amp;S
as the UK's most profitable retailer, with an increase of more than 17 per
cent in full-year pre-tax figures to about Pounds 865m. Analysts expect
gross margins to have been held and further cost savings to have led to an
increase of a percentage point or more in the net margin.
Argyll: Tough conditions in the grocery market and new depreciation policies
are likely to be reflected on Wednesday in a fall in full-year pre-tax
profits at the UK's third largest grocery retailer. The consensus among
analysts is for about Pounds 365m, down from Pounds 417m after a new Pounds
40m depreciation charge.
Land Securities: The extent of the recovery in commercial property values
will be underlined on Wednesday when the UK's largest quoted property
company reports its final results.
After three years of steeply falling net asset values, the company's nav is
expected to have rise from 504p per share to 630p-660p.
Pre-tax profits are likely to remain static at around Pounds 233m.
Cable &amp; Wireless: Analysts are forecasting pre-tax profits of more than
Pounds 1bn for the UK telecoms group, about 27 per cent up on the previous
year's (Pounds 824m). However, better-than-expected results announced last
Thursday at Hongkong Telecom, C&amp;W's largest business, may make that view
somewhat pessimistic.
</TEXT>
