<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAY 94 / British Coal paid under Pounds 1/2m by subsidy scheme:
Ministers indicated millions were on offer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A coal subsidy scheme, which helped the government suppress a backbench
revolt over pit closures last year, has provided British Coal with less than
Pounds 500,000 from the several hundreds of millions of pounds that
ministers indicated were available.
Although private-sector mining companies are also benefiting, it is likely
that the final bill for the scheme, which ends next March, will amount to
less than Pounds 10m.
The figures will be used by the Labour Party to support its claims that the
subsidy scheme was a cosmetic exercise aimed at saving the jobs of ministers
rather than miners.
However, the Department of Trade and Industry says the low subsidy level is
the result of the weak market which prompted it to implement pit closures in
the first place.
In addition, the subsidies bill would have been several million pounds
higher had British Coal not closed Ellington, one of its few pits to win
aid.
The promise of subsidies was a cornerstone of a government strategy last
March in which ministers 'reprieved' 12 pits from closure while British Coal
looked for markets for their coal.
Most of the reprieved pits have since closed, along with several others
which then looked safe. However the strategy enabled the government to
defeat an opposition motion over its coal policy.
British Coal would not comment yesterday. However it is understood to have
stopped applying for subsidies after complaining the rules of the scheme
were so tightly drawn that aid was rarely granted. That means the sum of
less than Pounds 500,000 it has already received will not increase.
Under the rules of the scheme, no profitable pit is allowed a subsidy and
only those pits with the potential to become profitable in three years can
qualify. In addition, sales from stocks cannot be subsidised.
In last March's coal white paper, the government said it was prepared to
'embrace the range of figures' on subsidies put forward by a House of
Commons industry select committee.
The committee had sought a subsidy until 1998, saying the total cost would
be unlikely to exceed Pounds 500m.
Mr Tim Eggar, energy minister, told parliament this month his department had
offered four subsidies, two to British Coal and two to the private sector,
and was considering another. In 1993 it paid out about Pounds 1m.
The DTI said yesterday that more than that had been paid out in 1994
already, but would not say how much. It said it had received further claims
for subsidies.
Whitehall sources say the biggest subsidy, Pounds 1.8m, was won this year by
the independent Monktonhall pit in Scotland.
</TEXT>
<XX>
