<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAY 94 / DTI seeks more scrutiny of insolvency fees
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Department of Trade and Industry is considering how to scrutinise more
effectively the fees charged by insolvency practitioners.
The move is in response to public concern over insolvency fees charged in
several recent high-profile corporate collapses.
Senior officials at the department plan to hold talks with professional
bodies and regulators covering the insolvency sector during the coming weeks
to decide how best to respond to criticism.
The discussions will focus on efforts to improve the transparency of fees
charged and ways to motivate creditors to consider whether practitioners are
achieving value for money.
Last July the Commons social security committee called for an independent
monitor in larger insolvencies to help determine whether practitioners'
actions and fees were appropriate. Government ministers rejected the
suggestion of an independent monitor and are opposed to any legislative
change or extensive involvement by civil servants in monitoring insolvency
practices more closely.
However, officials are trying to develop ways to encourage creditors to take
more seriously their role in approving practitioners' work programmes and
fees.
The result of the discussions might be codes of conduct or other voluntary
measures issued by the professional bodies during the coming months.
Touche Ross, the accountancy firm which is working on the liquidation of the
Bank of Credit and Commerce International, reported this month that its fees
since appointment at the end of 1991 exceeded Pounds 98m.
Last month the Commons social security committee criticised Buchler
Phillips, a specialist insolvency firm, in a report which highlighted that
it had barely recovered assets to pay for its fees in its work on the estate
of the publishing tycoon Robert Maxwell.
Other substantial professional fees have been incurred over the handling of
the companies in the Maxwell business empire and on the administration of
Polly Peck International.
The profession argues that the fees reflect the work firms have had to do
and are generally a small proportion of the total asset recoveries made as a
result of their efforts.
The renewed scrutiny comes at a time when the Joint Insolvency Monitoring
Unit, the new regulatory body for the profession, is also turning its
attention to fees during its random inspections of practitioners.
Ms Kay Linnell, the head of the unit, said inspections would consider how
reasonable charge rates were and the accuracy of time records. 'I do think
there are reasons for concern,' she said.
</TEXT>
