<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAY 94 / Airport dismisses safety allegations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Manchester Airport, which faces a tough fight to get permission to build a
second runway at a planning inquiry next month, last night denied aircraft
were being endangered by problems with navigation aids.
The allegations - seen in some quarters as part of a dirty-tricks campaign
to try to discredit the airport - were contained in a Sunday newspaper
report.
The Civil Aviation Authority, which licenses airports for safety, supported
Manchester's protests. 'If the CAA felt there was any problem, Manchester
would not have a licence,' the authority said last night.
The public inquiry begins on June 21.
A report in The Sunday Telegraph alleged malfunctioning landing lights and
inaccurate information from the airport's control tower on wind speed and
direction. The airport was also criticised for only having one windsock,
after investigation of a 1985 accident recommended more.
The authority said one pilot had filed an 'occurrence report' this year
after landing lights malfunctioned. Investigation had revealed electrical
interference caused by maintenance work. The authority said that the
incident was iso-lated.
A second pilot's report of inaccurate wind-speed information is still being
investigated. However, the authority said wind variations and gusts cannot
be predicted, which is why pilots are trained to deal with them on landing.
The airport said neither pilot had complained to the Manchester authorities,
which are responsible for about 250,000 take-offs and landings a year.
The CAA said only one windsock was needed. In an aircraft fire on the
Manchester runway in 1985, lives may have been lost because the pilot turned
the aircraft so that flames blew on to the fuselage. 'But more windsocks
would not help in a similar situation at night when you cannot see them,'
the authority said.
Last year more than 13m people used Manchester, Europe's fastest-growing
airport, which expects to pass Copenhagen to take sixth place in the
European size league shortly.
A second runway is widely supported in the region, particularly by business,
but is opposed by some residents. It would increase capacity to 30m
passengers early next century.
</TEXT>
