<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAY 94 / Health purchasing changes proposed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government is likely to be urged this week to set up an experiment that
would make 10 to 15 local authorities responsible for purchasing health
services.
Local councils and health authorities are being drawn into growing
disagreement over the running of the National Health Service.
A paper going to the Association of Metropolitan Authorities policy
committee on Thursday argues that switching health-purchasing
responsibilities from district health authorities to local councils could
produce better management, service planning and public accountability.
The paper calls for a pilot project under which local authorities of varying
size, type and geographical location would take over health commissioning.
Local authorities have never had a direct role in the NHS since its
foundation in 1948. One of the traditional arguments against local authority
involvement - lack of suitable expertise to run hospitals - has been
diminished by the government's 1991 NHS reforms. Hospitals are now run by
their own trust boards, with purchasing decisions made at arm's length by
district health authorities.
Critics in local authorities say unelected health authorities lack the
legitimacy or public standing to make difficult decisions about spending
priorities. They believe the government's decision to make local authorities
responsible for purchasing community care services adds force to the
argument that they should take over the entire health purchasing role.
The proposal is being fiercely resisted by the National Association of
Health Authorities and Trusts, which believes it could undermine the
national character of the NHS.
Mr Philip Hunt, the association's director, said health authorities were
accountable to the health secretary and were scrutinised by the Audit
Commission, the National Audit Office and other public watchdogs.
It was, however, important that appointees had credibility within their
local communities. 'Every effort should be made to encourage people from a
wide cross-section of the community to put their names forward for
appointment as chairmen and non-executive directors of NHS boards,' he said.
