<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAY 94 / Post Office chiefs accused of sell-off plot
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Post Office senior managers were accused yesterday of conspiring with Mr
Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, to try to achieve full
privatisation of postal services.
Mr Alan Johnson, the UCW postal union's general secretary, told his union's
annual conference that Mr Bill Cockburn, the Post Office chief executive,
had been involved in a 'pernicious plot' with Mr Heseltine but this had been
defeated at the last moment in the cabinet, partly as a result of the
union's pressure.
Mr Johnson said the union had 'achieved the first objective in the campaign
to oppose privatisation' with the government's decision that Parcelforce is
not to be sold off separately from the rest of the postal services.
At the weekend Mr Cockburn sent letters to the Post Office's 150,000
employees making it clear that he wants to see the Royal Mail's
privatisation. 'This is the only way absolutely to guarantee us all the
freedom we need to fight off foreign competition, protect jobs and invest
more freely in our future,' Mr Cockburn said.
But Mr Johnson said a third of all postal workers would lose their jobs if
the government eventually decided to break up the Post Office and privatise
it.
Until now the UCW and the Post Office have worked closely in support of
giving the service more commercial freedom. But the union is opposed to any
split of the mail and postal services from counter operations, and to giving
the private sector a majority shareholding.
The union's leaders are increasingly confident that public opinion will
deter the government from complete privatisation and that it will agree to
the option of leaving the business in the public sector but extending its
commercial freedom. The union believes this proposal will be introduced into
Mr Heseltine's consultative document on the Post Office's future, expected
to be published next month.
Replying to Mr Johnson's speech, Mr Cockburn said yesterday that
privatisation would 'protect jobs not threaten them', and accused the UCW of
scaremongering. 'Leaving the Post Office locked in the public sector would
be a recipe for disaster,' he said. 'The union is being profoundly
complacent and living in an unreal world. Time is not on our side.'
On Wednesday the powerful Federation of Women's Institutes, Age Concern and
other pressure groups are due to launch a campaign in defence of existing
postal services. They will demand at least six months for consultation when
Mr Heseltine publishes his green paper. Delegates questioned at the UCW's
conference yesterday were convinced the government would not proceed with
any privatisation plans for the Post Office.
</TEXT>
<XX>
