FT  23 MAY 94 / Safety body set to urge more regulation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Greater regulation of health and safety in various high-risk occupations is
likely to be recommended to the government tomorrow by the Health and Safety
Commission.
Seven taskforces, with representatives from business, have been examining
health and safety regulations, their costs and benefits in areas such as
construction.
They have reported back to the HSC, which will publish its recommendations
to the government shortly after Mr John Major, the prime minister, announces
the competitiveness white paper.
It is understood that the HSC will say that there are various areas of high
risk in which current legislative controls are inadequate and that new
goal-setting regulations are needed.
Mr Kevin Barron, Labour's health and safety spokesman, said yesterday that
in 1992-93, 368 people died as a result of accidents at work in the UK while
143,244 serious accidents were reported to the Health and Safety Executive.
