<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAY 94 / Early cut likely in Commons hours
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A drastic reduction in the number of hours that parliament sits could be
implemented within months amid signs that government and opposition business
managers are set to make progress in talks on the issue.
Concern over the heavy Commons workload on MPs, highlighted by the recent
death of John Smith, the Labour leader, has injected an urgency into the
approach of Conservative and Labour business managers towards the issue of
restricting the Commons timetable.
The issue will be discussed later this week at a meeting led by Mr Tony
Newton, the leader of the House, and Mr Nick Brown, his acting counterpart,
for Labour.
Measures being considered include the conclusion of more Commons business by
10pm, the introduction of Wednesday morning sittings and the allocation of
10 free Fridays per year in which MPs could visit their constituencies.
The government side will claim at this week's meeting that the measures
could be introduced quickly through the Commons' standing orders rather than
primary legislation.
Labour business managers have also said they may be willing to give way on
several demands from the government which are essential to any agreement for
reducing the length of sittings. A senior Labour MP said the party would
view favourably the request that more bills should be informally timetabled
so that votes could be taken after a specified period. 'There is a
willingness on our part to make reasonable arrangements,' he said.
Progress could also be made to ensure that more bills are subjected to
detailed examination in standing committees rather than on the floor of the
Commons.
Labour's front bench may find an agreement hard to sell to backbenchers
after a row earlier this year over the guillotining of bills arising from
the Budget. Labour introduced a period of non-co-operation with Tory whips
in protest at the move.
However, the government is keen to get an agreement on the Commons
timetable, partly because it needs to improve the efficiency with which
bills are considered. According to ministers, the amount of legislation
proposed by Whitehall departments for next year's session is already three
times greater than the parliamentary time available, and an agreement with
Labour might allow more bills to be considered.
Ministers are concerned that several bills due to be considered in the
1994-95 session - including the pensions bill - will weigh heavily on
Commons time.
</TEXT>
