<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAY 94 / Brown makes appeal to tradition: Leadership contest
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By:BY ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, yesterday made a strong appeal to
Labour's socialist past as a guide to the party's future, in a speech
carefully pitched at the traditional Labour mainstream. Combined with
repeated attacks on privatisation, the City and means-testing for welfare,
the speech was clearly aimed at the prejudices of the constituency and union
rank-and-file at Labour's annual Welsh conference.
In his keynote speech to the 500 delegates meeting at Swansea for the
one-day conference - truncated in the wake of John Smith's death - Mr Brown
called for party unity and made no mention of the coming leadership contest.
He also committed Labour to a University for Industry, partnership between
the public and private sectors and a readiness to grasp the opportunities of
the dawning new information age and the permanent industrial revolution now
in train.
But the tone of Mr Brown's speech was firmly traditionalist, laced with
appeals to socialist values 'that do not change. Let us have confidence that
our values are the values of the people of this country,' he told the
delegates, in what some saw as a clear effort to distance himself from
Labour's more radical modernisers.
Privatisation and the City were the targets of sustained invective. Mr Brown
contrasted 'neglected public services' with 'international companies using
and abusing Britain as a tax haven, directors of the privatised industries
overpaying themselves so grossly . . . (and) the waste, short-terminism and
costly failure of self-regulation in the City of London'.
In place of 'dividends-hungry' financial institutions, Mr Brown called for
'long-term investment agreements between UK companies and banks and
pension-funds investors'.
He said that an investments revolution lay at the core of Labour's
industrial policy.
He also recommitted Labour to a national minimum wage and a windfall tax on
the profits of privatised utilities. The tax would be used to help fund
radical measures to expand the capacity of the economy, including an
emergency employment programme and active regional and industrial policies.
Mr Brown had little to say about Europe except to condemn Conservative
divisions on the issue and to repeat Labour's support for a European
recovery fund and the social chapter of the Maastricht treaty.
The speech was well received by delegates, who had earlier debated
employment and the welfare state, including a motion calling for full
employment to be a key objective of a future Labour government.
Outside the conference hall the mood of delegates appeared to be in favour
of a contested leadership election. One said there was strong resentment in
south Wales constituency parties at the 'media bandwagon' for Mr Tony Blair,
the shadow home secretary.
Several delegates volunteered support for Mr John Prescott, shadow
employment secretary, because of his emphasis on full employment and his
rapport with Labour's grassroots.
A constituency official from Newport summed up the mood of one group in the
bar: 'Blair may be the man to win the election - but at least he should be
forced to debate the issues with John Prescott.'
Mr Brown's appeal to Labour's roots in Welsh trade unionism - 'from its
small beginnings in valleys and pit villages' in the late 19th century -
could be seen as the start of a campaign to cultivate union support.
Trade unionists make up one-third of Labour's leadership electoral college.
Mr Brown spoke to the hearts and concerns of Welsh union officials in his
audience with his commitments on employment, means-testing for benefits and
a 'strategy for coal' to revive the Welsh valleys, the cradle and bastion of
the 20th-century Labour party.
'We are sustained by our enduring values, handed down from one generation to
another, values that do not change,' Mr Brown said.
</TEXT>
