<DATELINE>
   CAPE TOWN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
President Nelson Mandela's African National Congress yesterday chose its
secretary-general, Mr Cyril Ramaphosa, as chairman of an assembly that will
draft a permanent non-racial constitution for South Africa, Reuter reports
from Cape Town.
Legislator and party spokesman Arnold Stofile told reporters that Mr
Ramaphosa, 41, was unanimously elected to head the 490-member Constitutional
Assembly, which will sit for the first time tomorrow.
The Constitutional Assembly will comprise members of the National Assembly
elected in the country's first all-race polls last month and senators
appointed by nine post-apartheid provincial parliaments last week.
